pullRequest.title: Test code coverage publishing
pullRequest.bodyText:
This PR enables publishing code coverage report to DevOps build pipeline tab. The intent of this change is to collect aggregate test coverage report for track 2 client libraries under each service directory (sdk/). In order to generate this as an aggregate report at the service level, this PR makes 2 main changes:
Update to service pom.xml
Since JaCoCo's aggregate report does not work on an aggregator module (i.e. the existing service pom.xml), the official recommended strategy is to create a dummy module to include all track 2 modules of a service as a dependency and use this dummy module to generate the aggregate report. However, I was able to repurpose the aggregator pom.xml by using profiles to make the aggregator pom look like the dummy module when the coverage profile is activated by including -Pcoverage option when running the maven command. By default, the service pom.xml will just be an aggregator, as it previously was, which includes only a list of modules. When generating the report, the coverage profile will be activated which will then have the dependencies and the maven goal to generate the jacoco report.
Update the client pipeline yml to publish coverage report
To publish the coverage report, there are 2 new steps added to the pipeline

Generate the aggregate report: This step is run immediately after the unit tests are run. This step uses the service pom.xml and activates the coverage profile and targets the jacoco:report-aggregate maven goal to generate the jacoco.xml file in sdk//target/site/jacoco-coverage` directory.
Publish the report - this is a standard DevOps step that supports publishing JaCoCo reports.

Both these steps are enabled to run only for Windows + JDK 11 combination.
This PR enables publishing test coverage for template as proof of concept. If this is an acceptable solution, I'll extend it to other services.
fixes #17316
fixes #17317
